  - name: Encode
    commands:
      - title: Generate PNG from string
        command: barcode -b '0123456789abcdABCD' -e code128 -g 400x225 -u pt -E | magick - -background white -alpha remove -alpha off out.png
        options:
          -b: string to encode (use input file if missing)
          -e: encoding type (default is best fit for first string)
          -g: "geometry on the page: [<wid>x<hei>][+<margin>+<margin>]; Note that an additional white margin of 10 points is added to the printout."
          -u: unit ("mm", "in", ...)
          -E: "print one code as eps file (default: multi-page ps)"
      - title: Generate SVG from string
        description: svgo is optional to reduce the size of the generated image. Be careful though, it might break the output!
        command: barcode -b 'andreas-mausch.de' -e code128 -g 400x225 -u pt -S | svgo - > out.svg
      - title: Generate with zint
        command: zint --barcode=20 --data='0123456789abcdABCD' --scale=4 --output=out.png
        options:
          --barcode: -b, Barcode type, see -t for all available types. Can also be a string like CODE128.
          --data: -d, Data to encode
          --scale: Increase size
          --output: -o, Output file
          --filetype: Will be detected automatically by the output file naming. Supported types are BMP, EMF, EPS, GIF, PCX, PNG, SVG, TIF, TXT.
  - name: Decode
    commands:
      - title: via zbarimg
        command: zbarimg code.png

# Code39 vs. Code128

> - A Code 128 barcode can encode a full 128 ASCII character set. A Code 39 barcode encodes 39 characters in total.
> - Code 128 has a higher density than Code 39.
> - Code 39 does not include a check digit, while Code 128 does.
> -- <https://www.dynamsoft.com/blog/insights/code-39-vs-code-128/>

# Differences between Code128 A, B, C

> - 128A (Code Set A) – ASCII characters 00 to 95 (0–9, A–Z and control codes), special characters, and FNC 1–4
> - 128B (Code Set B) – ASCII characters 32 to 127 (0–9, A–Z, a–z), special characters, and FNC 1–4
> - 128C (Code Set C) – 00–99 (encodes two digits with a single code point) and FNC1
> -- <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_128#Subtypes>

So if your string only contains digits, you can use Set C to save some space.

# Error correction and checksum

Code128 does have a checksum character, while Code39 does not.
However, neither has any type of error correction with redundant data, like in QR codes.
